T1  - On having your cake and eating it too: Econometric problems in estimating the demand for health services
AU  - Newhouse, Joseph P.
AU  - Phelps, Charles E.
AU  - Marquis, M.Susan
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 13
IS  - 3
SP  - 365
EP  - 390
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/08/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(80)90085-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407680900858
AB  - ‘On Having Your Cake and Eating It Too: Econometric Problems in Estimating the Demand for Health Services’ discusses certain methodological problems in the economics literature related to the demand for medical care. Two principal problems are examined: misspecification of how insurance affects demand and aggregation across services or across individuals. The article shows that in both cases estimates contained in the literature are inconsistent. Where possible, the direction of the inconsistency is obtained a priori. The article also makes estimates of the magnitude of the inconsistency; the demand elasticities estimated in the economics literature may be overstated by a factor of three or more.
